About this dataset Age : Age of the patient

Sex : Sex of the patient

exang: exercise induced angina (1 = yes; 0 = no)

ca: number of major vessels (0-3)

cp : Chest Pain type chest pain type

Value 1: typical angina Value 2: atypical angina Value 3: non-anginal pain Value 4: asymptomatic trtbps : resting blood pressure (in mm Hg)

chol : cholestoral in mg/dl fetched via BMI sensor

fbs : (fasting blood sugar > 120 mg/dl) (1 = true; 0 = false)

rest_ecg : resting electrocardiographic results

thalachh : maximum heart rate achieved

exng : exercise induced angina (1 = yes; 0 = no)

oldpeak : Previous peak

Value 0: normal Value 1: having ST-T wave abnormality (T wave inversions and/or ST elevation or depression of > 0.05 mV) Value 2: showing probable or definite left ventricular hypertrophy by Estes' criteria thalach : maximum heart rate achieved

target : 0= less chance of heart attack 1= more chance of heart attack

Now let us have a look at the proportion of the different types of chest pains reported.

In [8]:
plt.figure(figsize=(9,5))
plt.title('Chest Pain Type', fontdict={'fontweight': 'bold'})
typical_angina=df.loc[df.cp==0].count()[0]
atypical_angina=df.loc[df.cp==1].count()[0]
non_anginal= df.loc[df.cp==2].count()[0]
Asymptomatic= df.loc[df.cp==3].count()[0]

label=['Typical Angina','Atypical Angina', 'Non-Anginal pain', 'Asymptomatic']

plt.pie([typical_angina,atypical_angina,non_anginal,Asymptomatic], labels= label, autopct= '%.0f %%')
plt.show()

Typical Angina is a type of chest pain caused by reduced blood flow to the heart which makes it a strong indicator of heart disease and can help identify patients at higher risk for a heart attack. Atypical Angina and Non-Anginal Pain can also be symptoms of heart disease and should not be overlooked. Asymptomatic individuals with heart disease may not present with chest pain, making it important to consider other risk factors and diagnostic tests. So from the plot,the types of chest pains show that 47% of the people are more likely to develop heart attack faster with the rest also being likely develop heart attack.

Visualing the the distribution of cholesterol level.

In [9]:
plt.figure(figsize=(7,4))
plt.title('Distribution of Cholesterol Level')
sns.distplot(df.chol)
plt.show()

This show that the cholesterol level of most of the people are within or above the borderline which is 200 to 239mg/dL. Those above this range are at High cholesterol level(of which most people in the data are) and those below this range have normal cholesterol levels. High levels of cholesterol can lead to the buildup of plaque in the arteries, restricting blood flow to the heart.This buildup of plaque can increase the risk of heart disease and heart attack. Lowering cholesterol levels through lifestyle changes and medication can help reduce the risk of heart disease and heart attack. From the plot, most patients in the data have high risk of high attack due to the higher density for higher cholesterol levels.

Let us have a look at the fasting blood sugar levels

In [10]:
data=df.copy()
data['fbs']=data['fbs'].replace({0: 'less than 120', 1:'greater than 120'})


plt.figure(figsize=(7,4))
plt.title('Distribution of Fasting Blood Sugar Level')
sns.histplot(data.fbs)
plt.show()

The data do not specify the actual levels for individuals but from this, we can determine their diabetes status; A fasting blood sugar level of 99 mg/dL or lower is normal, 100 to 125 mg/dL indicates you have prediabetes, and 126 mg/dL or higher indicates you have diabetes. So very few people in the data are diabetic, approximately 50 in number.Individuals with diabetes are at higher risk for developing heart disease and heart attack, as high blood sugar levels can damage the blood vessels and increase the buildup of plaque in the arteries.

Analayzing relationships¶

Let have a look at the relationship between age and cholesterol level males and females.

In [11]:
data=df.copy()
data['sex']= data['sex'].replace({1:'female', 0:'male'})

sns.lmplot(x='age',y= 'chol',hue='sex' ,data=data)
Out[11]:
<seaborn.axisgrid.FacetGrid at 0x924a5c8090>

From the plot,we could see that for males, cholesterol level has a positive correlation with age and thus, increases with age generally(remember other factors like alcohol intake are not considered here). Also,with female, there is a positive correlation between cholesterol level and age but it is lower at most ages compared to the cholesterol level of males.

Let us have a look at the relationship between age and resting blood pressure for males and females.

In [12]:
sns.lmplot(x='age',y= 'trtbps',hue='sex' ,data=data)
Out[12]:
<seaborn.axisgrid.FacetGrid at 0x924e8a9c50>

The plot shows that generally, the resting blood pressure increases with age. For males, resting blood pressure's dependence on age is higher than females. The increase in resting blood pressure with age may be due to factors such as stiffening of the arteries, decreased elasticity of the blood vessels, and increased plaque buildup in the arteries. This can lead to an increased workload on the heart and a higher risk of heart disease and heart attack. Therefore, monitoring blood pressure and taking steps to maintain healthy blood pressure levels can be important for preventing heart disease and heart attack.

Let's see how blood sugar level and age are related too.

In [13]:
data=df.copy()
diabetic=data.loc[data.fbs==1]
non_diabetic= data.loc[data.fbs==0]

plt.figure(figsize=(5,3))
plt.title('Age Distribution of patients with FBS > 120mg/dl')
sns.distplot(diabetic.age)
plt.figure(figsize=(5,3))
plt.title('Age Distribution of of patients with FBS < 120mg/dl')
sns.distplot(non_diabetic.age)
Out[13]:
<AxesSubplot: title={'center': 'Age Distribution of of patients with FBS < 120mg/dl'}, xlabel='age', ylabel='Density'>

From the plots we could know that age distribution of people with fasting blood sugar levels greater 120mg/dl has a higher density at ages above 50years whiles age distribution for those with FBS lower that 120mg/dl has a higher density for a wider age range. Patients with FBS greater that 120 mg/dl are likely to be diabetic and develop heart attack faster. Fasting blood sugar (FBS) levels tend to increase with age due to changes in insulin resistance and decreased pancreatic function. This can increase the risk of developing diabetes, which is a major risk factor for heart disease and heart attack.

Now let us have a look as to whether there is a relationship between cholesterol level and resting blood pressure,and their role in determining the chance of a person developing heart attack.

In [14]:
data=df.copy()
data['output']= data['output'].replace({1:'High chance',0:'low chance'})
sns.lmplot(x='trtbps',y= 'chol', hue='output',data=data)
Out[14]:
<seaborn.axisgrid.FacetGrid at 0x924ea1a550>

The plot shows that for both patients with high and low chance of developing heart attack, cholesterol levels has a positive correlation. Increased cholesterol levels can lead to atherosclerosis and narrowing of the arteries, which can contribute to higher resting blood pressure due to increased resistance to blood flow.

Model to predict chance of heart attack.¶

In [15]:
from sklearn.ensemble import RandomForestClassifier
from sklearn.metrics import mean_absolute_error
from sklearn.model_selection import train_test_split
from sklearn.linear_model import PassiveAggressiveRegressor
In [16]:
X= df.drop(columns=['output'])
y=df.output

X_train,X_test,y_train,y_valid= train_test_split(X,y,test_size=0.2,random_state=72)

my_model= RandomForestClassifier(n_estimators=500 , max_depth= 100, random_state=72)

my_model.fit(X_train,y_train)
predictions = my_model.predict(X_test)

efficiency = my_model.score(X_test, y_valid)

mae= mean_absolute_error(y_valid,predictions)
print('model accuracy:', efficiency)
print('mean absolute error:', mae)

model accuracy: 0.8852459016393442
mean absolute error: 0.11475409836065574
